Part 1 - Number of lines said per character throughout the play

Pre-emble

library(formattable)
library(tokenizers)

#Loading data and converting to matrix of paragraphs
data=readLines("hamlet1.txt")
par_tok = tokenize_paragraphs(data, paragraph_break = "\n\n", simplify = TRUE)
par_tok_mat = as.matrix(par_tok)
par_tok_mat = as.character(par_tok_mat)

#Assigning HAMLET play character names. I have chosen to only include those that had over 100 lines and I added a couple with the fewest lines as controls

names=c("HAMLET ", "CLAUDIUS ", "POLONIUS ", "HORATIO ", "LAERTES ", "GERTRUDE ", "OPHELIA ", "BERNARDO ", "FORTINBRAS ")

ACT1 =grep("ACT I",par_tok_mat, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE) 
ACT2 =grep("ACT II",par_tok_mat, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE) 
ACT3 =grep("ACT III",par_tok_mat, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE) 
ACT4 =grep("ACT IV",par_tok_mat, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE) 
ACT5 =grep("ACT V",par_tok_mat, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE) 

#Exclude all line before ACT I
par_tok_mat=par_tok_mat[ACT1[1]:length(par_tok_mat)]
par_tok_mat[1]
[1] "ACT I"
#Replace all lines staring with [ with a blank character
brackets=grep("\\[",par_tok_mat, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE) 
par_tok_mat[brackets]=" "

Line counting loop

#At the first instance of character's name, count number of lines before an empty line
#Loop through the whole script and go back into the loop for the next character's name on the list

for (k in 1:length(names)) {
  name=names[k]
  count=0
  act1_count=0
  act2_count=0
  act3_count=0
  act4_count=0
  act5_count=0

 name_x = grep(name, par_tok_mat, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE)

     for(i in 1:length(name_x)) {
    
          for (j in 1:length(par_tok_mat)) {
            
              if (par_tok_mat[name_x[i]+j] == "character(0)") {
              count=count+j
    
              if (name_x[i] < ACT2[1]) {
              act1_count=act1_count+j
        }
              
        if (name_x[i] >= ACT2[1] & name_x[i] < ACT3[1]) {
        act2_count=act2_count+j }
     
        if (name_x[i] >= ACT3[1] & name_x[i] < ACT4[1]) {
        act3_count=act3_count+j }
   
        if (name_x[i] >= ACT4[1] & name_x[i] < ACT5[1]) {
        act4_count=act4_count+j }
   
        if (name_x[i] > ACT5[1]) {
        act5_count=act5_count+j }

         break}
     }
  
    assign(paste0("count.", name) , count)
    assign(paste0("act1_count.", name) , act1_count)
    assign(paste0("act2_count.", name) , act2_count)
    assign(paste0("act3_count.", name) , act3_count)
    assign(paste0("act4_count.", name) , act4_count)
    assign(paste0("act5_count.", name) , act5_count)
   }  
}

Part 2 - Word cloud of unusual words in the script

Pre-emble

#Load libraries and import data
library(tm)
library(wordcloud)
library(tidyverse)

data=readLines("hamlet1.txt")
play <- Corpus(VectorSource(data))

#Use existing TM functions to tidy up data
play <- play %>%
  tm_map(removeNumbers) %>%
  tm_map(removePunctuation) %>%
  tm_map(stripWhitespace)
transformation drops documentstransformation drops documentstransformation drops documents
play <- tm_map(play, content_transformer(tolower))
transformation drops documents
play <- tm_map(play, removeWords, stopwords("english"))
transformation drops documents
#Create data frame of word frequency counts
dtm <- TermDocumentMatrix(play) 
matrix <- as.matrix(dtm) 
words <- sort(rowSums(matrix),decreasing=TRUE) 
df <- data.frame(word = names(words),freq=words)

Explore how to define unusual words

barplot(df[1:30,]$freq, las = 2, names.arg = df[1:30,]$word,
        col ="lightpink", main ="Most frequent words in Hamlet",
        ylab = "Word frequencies")


#Download 10000 most common English words https://github.com/first20hours/google-10000-english
lemma <- read.csv("dictionary.txt", sep="")

#Perform inner-left join between Hamplet play and the dictinary
dfx= merge(x = df, y = lemma, by = "word", all.x = TRUE)

#Find words that are in Hamlet play but not in the English dictionary and classify them as potentially unusual
new_df <- dfx[is.na(dfx$rank),]

#Sort frequency in descending order - unusual words don't have to be rare in the Hamlet play
dfz = new_df[order(-new_df$freq),]
head(dfz,20)

barplot(dfz[1:30,]$freq, las = 2, names.arg = dfz[1:30,]$word,
        col ="lightpink", main ="Most frequent unusual words in Hamlet",
        ylab = "Word frequencies")



#Explore unusual/frequent problem further and remove top 50 most frequent words in the remainder of the data
dfz1=dfz[dfz$freq<50,]

barplot(dfz1[1:30,]$freq, las = 2, names.arg = dfz1[1:30,]$word,
        col ="lightpink", main ="Most frequent unusual words in Hamlet with frequency of under 50",                ylab = "Word frequencies")

Part 3 - Compute the sentiment score for each scene

Pre-emble

library(tidytext)
library(textdata)
library(formattable)

data=readLines("hamlet1.txt")
scene_lines=grep("SCENE ",data, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE)

act1=grep("ACT I",data, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE)
act2=grep("ACT II",data, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE)
act3=grep("ACT III",data, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE)
act4=grep("ACT IV",data, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE)
act5=grep("ACT V",data, value=FALSE, ignore.case=FALSE, fixed=FALSE)
act_lines=c(act1[1], act2[1], act3[1], act4[1], act5[1])

#Data wrangling - partitioning the text into acts and scenes, storing it in separate dataframes and then binding them all together at the end
j=0
df=data.frame()
for (i in 1:length(scene_lines)) {
  
  if (scene_lines[i]<act_lines[2]) {
    name = data[scene_lines[i]:scene_lines[i+1]]
      text=glue(read_file(name))
      j=j+1
      tokens = tibble(text = name) %>%      
      unnest_tokens(word, text)
    
      tokens$act=1
      tokens$scene=j
      df=rbind(df, tokens)
      k=0 }
      
  
 if (scene_lines[i]<act_lines[3] & scene_lines[i]>act_lines[2]) {
    name = data[scene_lines[i]:scene_lines[i+1]]
      text=glue(read_file(name))
      k=k+1
      tokens = tibble(text = name) %>%      
      unnest_tokens(word, text)
    
      tokens$act=2
      tokens$scene=k
      df=rbind(df, tokens)
      l=0}
     

  if (scene_lines[i]<act_lines[4] & scene_lines[i]>act_lines[3]) {
    name = data[scene_lines[i]:scene_lines[i+1]]
      text=glue(read_file(name))
      l=l+1
      tokens = tibble(text = name) %>%      
      unnest_tokens(word, text)
    
      tokens$act=3
      tokens$scene=l
      df=rbind(df, tokens)
      m=0}

  if (scene_lines[i]<act_lines[5] & scene_lines[i]>act_lines[4]) {
    name = data[scene_lines[i]:scene_lines[i+1]]
      text=glue(read_file(name))
      m=m+1
      tokens = tibble(text = name) %>%      
      unnest_tokens(word, text)

      tokens$act=4
      tokens$scene=m
      df=rbind(df, tokens)
      n=0}

    if (scene_lines[i]>act_lines[5]) {
    name = data[scene_lines[i]:length(data)]
      text=glue(read_file(name))
      n=n+1
      tokens = tibble(text = name) %>%      
      unnest_tokens(word, text)
      
      tokens$act=5
      tokens$scene=n
      df=rbind(df, tokens)}
     }
